ANALYSIS OF HAZARDS INVOLVING COMPRESSED GAS FUELING AT
RETAIL SERVICE STATIONS

An evaluation of the hazards associated with operations
of a typical compressed natural gas (CNG) fueling
station is presented (by Total Petroleum Inc.).  The
evaluation includes: identification of a typical CNG
fueling system; a comparison of the typical system with
ANSI/NFPA (American National Standards
Institute/National Fire Protection Association)
Standard 52 Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) Vehicular Fuel
System requirements; a review of CNG industry safety
experience as identified in current literature; hazard
identification of potential internal and external
events leading to potential accidents; and an analysis
of potential accident scenarios as determined from the
hazard evaluation.  The study considers CNG dispensing
equipment and associated equipment, including the
compressor station, storage vessels, and fill pressure-
sensing system.

(Order this ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS & REMEDIATION
reviewed report from InfoTeam Inc., P.O. Box 15640,
Plantation, FL 33318-5640; Phone (954)/or(305)
473-9560, Fax (954)/or(305) 473-0544: Report No.
N960107; Apr. 1995, 156 pp.  Price: $179.00, prepaid.)




